         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">29/1/83. ¶  ¶ In continuation of former communications on Cycadeae ¶  I wish to tell you, dear Mr Dyer, that I have at the Gov. photographic Office now a ripe female amentum of Macrozamia Douglasii fo...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">83.01.29b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Thiselton-Dyer</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 47-49.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">29/1/83.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In continuation of former communications on <name key="Cycadeae">Cycadeae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Most of M’s letters to W. Thiselton-Dyer in 1882 mention the supply of specimens or photographs of Macrozamia, Zamia or Cycas spp.</p>
               </note> I wish to tell you, dear Mr Dyer, that I have at the Gov. photographic Office now a ripe female amentum of <name key="Macrozamia%20Douglasii">Macrozamia Douglasii</name> for you.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See A. McDowall to M, 17 January 1883.</p>
               </note> An account of this species will appear in the february Number of the Melbourne "Chemist",<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B83.02.01.</p>
               </note> through which periodical I am endeavouring to inspire the now numberous Pharmac. Gentlemen all over Australia, to help in obtaining locally material for the completion of the Austr. "Flora".<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For discussions of the proposal to supplement <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg>, see Lucas (2003), pp. 272–4, and Clements (1998).</p>
               </note> This Macrozamia, more even than M. Macdonnelli,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Macrozamia macdonnellii?</p>
               </note> shows the real transit to <name key="Encephalartos">Encephalartos</name> so far as the extreme abbreviation of its fruit-scales is concerned.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M described the species as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Encephalartos">Encephalartos</name> douglasii</seg>.</p>
               </note> Anatomical differences in the stems I have not S. Afric material to trace out. You will get nuts &amp;c when dry.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The hon. J. Thurston has now sent me also some detached male scales of <name key="Cycas%20Seemanni">Cycas Seemanni</name>,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Thurston to M, 13 January 1883.</p>
               </note> which if they are always of the same form show a great difference between them and those of C. [ci]rcinalis &amp; C. Rumphii. These scales belong to the var. with globular nuts, and construct an amentum of 2 – 2½ feet length, but only 4 - 4½ inches width. Also this you will receive, as I have asked Mr Thurston for photographic purposes to send a complete <seg>♂</seg> cone. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I further asked him, to try to get the <seg>♂</seg> of the oval and larger fruited Cycas of Fiji, as that would lead to a crucial test for settling, whether one or two Cycas-species occur in the extensive Fiji-Group. My Papuan collections are for want of space not accessible this moment, as I must constantly make some <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">shift</hi>
               </seg> or other, after being deprived of my house &amp;c. When I can get at them, I will look up the <name key="Cycas%20Papuana">Cycas Papuana</name> for you.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See W. Thiselton-Dyer to M, 24 November 1882.</p>
               </note> Dr Beccari ought to have specimens also. After the rejunction of <name key="Widdringtonia">Widdringtonia</name> with <name key="Callitris">Callitris</name>, the geographic separation of genera of Gymnosperms breaks down. </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">You will see a puerily article on the Melb. bot. Garden in Hayters Yearbook for 1881-1882,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Victorian year-book for 1881-2</seg>, pp. 489-91.</p>
               </note> probably written by the Curator.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>William Guilfoyle.</p>
               </note> A fine consolation to the poor selectors, to grow <name key="Ricinus">Ricinus</name>-seeds for lubrication-oil in competition of Indian labor at 2d or 3d a day!<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The article reports, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">inter alia</seg>, that 'some sixty or more persons — farmers, selectors, and others throughout the colony — have been supplied with seeds of <name key="Ricinus">Ricinus</name> communis — the castor oil tree — and other useful plants, for the purpose of testing their value as remunerative crops.'</p>
               </note> I gave <name key="Ricinus">Ricinus</name>-seeds away 30 years ago, to grow the plant for <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">medicinal</hi>
               </seg> oil locally, and to have the leaves as a galactagogue. The German Missionary Rev. Mr Hagenauer obtained 20 years ago the roots of <name key="Canna%20edulis">Canna edulis</name>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">from me</hi>
               </seg>; and already years <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">before</hi>
               </seg> the present <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Curator</hi>
               </seg> came <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">here</hi>
               </seg>, the Natives of the Mission-Station of Mr Hagenauer prepared this kind of Arrow root by the ctws!<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>cwts (= hundredweights)? The article reported that 'a vast quantity of a variety of arrowroot, <name key="Canna%20edulis">Canna edulis</name> … has been propagated and largely distributed. Some of the arrowroot manufactured from this plant is already in the market, having been prepared at the Ramahyuck Aboriginal Station, under the superintendence of the Rev. F. A. Hagenauer, as well as by other private enterprise.'</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This is what is proverbially called here "hoodwinking the people."</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When will the fourth vol. of the Flora Capensis<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The second section of the fourth volume of<seg style="font-style: italic; "> Flora capensis</seg>, edited by W. Thiselton-Dyer as a continuation of Harvey &amp; Sonder (1859-65), appeared in 1904; the first section was published in 1909 (Thiselton-Dyer (1896-1925)). Volume 6, the first continuation volume of Harvey &amp; Sonder (Dyer) was published out of sequence in 1896-7 (See TL2, entry 2448).</p>
               </note> be out?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Geneva; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are now witnessing here under Dr Rudall's hands the wonderful effect of the seeds of <name key="Abrus%20precatorius%20">Abrus precatorius </name>in ciliar Trichosis and for removing granulation without inoculation according to Dr de Weckers new method.<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The final sentence is the only text on f. 49, and is included here as a possible enclosure to this letter. Rudall reported using Jequirity, a common name for <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Abrus precatorius</seg>, to a meeting of the Victorian Branch of the British Medical Association in 1883 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus, </seg>26 May 1883, p. 5 col a); de Wecker had described its use in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Annales d’oculistique</seg>, vol 88, p. 24.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
